SIMPLE: girder
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Girder
<hw>Gird"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Gird</er> to
sneer at.]</ety> <def>One who girds; a satirist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Girder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Girder
<hw>Gird"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Gird</er> to
encircle.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, girds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch. & Engin.)</fld> <def>A main beam; a stright,
horizontal beam to span an opening or carry weight, such as ends of
floor beams, etc.; hence, a framed or built-up member discharging the
same office, technically called a <xex>compound girder</xex>. See
<xex>Illusts</xex>. of <er>Frame</er>, and <cref>Doubleframed
floor</cref>, under <er>Double</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Bowstring girder</b></col>, <col><b>Box
girder</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Bowstring</er>,
<er>Box</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Girder bridge</b></col>. <cd>See
under <er>Bridge</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Lattice girder</b></col>, <cd>a
girder consisting of longitudinal bars united by diagonal crossing
bars.</cd> -- <col><b>Half-lattice girder</b></col>, <cd>a girder
consisting of horizontal upper and lower bars connected by a series of
diagonal bars sloping alternately in opposite directions so as to divide
the space between the bars into a series of triangles.</cd>
<au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Sandwich girder</b></col>, <cd>a girder
consisting of two parallel wooden beams, between which is an iron plate,
the whole clamped together by iron bolts.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Girding</ent>⟦br⟧
